{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"20367171-2d48-494c-9362-70785488ded7","content":"The template has the basic structure but has several issues before it's NuGet-ready:\n\n**Missing required/recommended fields:**\n- **`$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation.\n- **`groupIdentity`** — Needed for NuGet template packs to group related templates.\n- **`defaultName`** — Controls the fallback project name (e.g., `\"WebApi1\"`).\n- **`preferNameDirectory`** — Should be `true` for project templates.\n\n**Functional issue:**\n- The `Framework` symbol has no **`replaces`** property, so selecting a framework won't actually substitute the `<TargetFramework>` value in your `.csproj`. You need something like `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"`.\n\n**Nice-to-haves:**\n- No `postActions` for automatic `dotnet restore`.\n- No `description` field at the top level — users won't know what the template does in `dotnet new list`.\n\n**Verdict: Not ready.** At minimum, add `groupIdentity`, `defaultName`, a top-level `description`, and fix the `Framework` symbol's `replaces` before publishing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"48652bb0-a09c-4a84-b030-fa483e68a5bf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nIssues I can see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** – Not strictly required, but recommended for validation/IntelliSense.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** – Recommended for template packs published to NuGet to group related templates.\n3. **Missing `precedence`** – Useful when multiple versions of a template exist.\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** – Minor, but good practice.\n5. **`sourceName`** is set to `MyWebApi` – This is fine, it's the namespace replacement token.\n\n\n6. **No `postActions`** defined – Not required but often useful for things like restoring NuGet packages.\n7. **Missing `defaultName`** – Unclear what happens when no name is provided.\n8. The `Framework` symbol doesn't have a `replaces` property, so it won't actually substitute anything in the template files unless there's additional configuration elsewhere.\n\nThe main blockers for NuGet publishing are the missing `$schema` and `groupIdentity` properties, plus the `Framework` symbol needs a `replaces` property to actually perform substitutions in the project files.","outputTokens":639,"requestId":"33CC:156A76:1F63D31:233C43A:69E81B4B"},"id":"18304553-4797-41f1-b31a-9a9b13a31761","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:50:33.965Z","parentId":"5ef68f00-a75c-4a54-beb1-e3d4937c950b"}
